<!--The main difference between this and the signin form is that we have no Session model, and hence no analogue for the @user variable. This means that, in constructing the new session form, we have to give form_for slightly more information; in particular, whereas: form_for(@user)
allows Rails to infer that the action of the form should be to POST to the URL /users, in the case of sessions we need to indicate the name of the resource and the corresponding URL:
form_for(:session, url: sessions_path) -->




<% provide(:title, "Sign in") %>
<h1>Sign in</h1>

<div class="row">
  <div class="span6 offset3">
    <%= form_for(:session, url: sessions_path) do |f| %>

      <%= f.label :email %>
      <%= f.text_field :email %>

      <%= f.label :password %>
      <%= f.password_field :password %>

      <%= f.submit "Sign in", class: "btn btn-large btn-primary" %>
    <% end %>

    <p>New user? <%= link_to "Sign up now!", signup_path %></p>
  </div>
</div>


